 a decomposing pumpkin about to be jettisoned, she stops, seeing in the rotting, squalid vegetable a special treasure. “I’ve never seen one quite like this before,” she says, and looks to see if any seeds remain. It is from moments like these that Herring builds his questions: What counts as an acceptable material life—and who decides? Is hoarding some sort of inherent deviation of the mind, or a recent historical phenomenon grounded in changing material cultures? Herring opts for the latter, explaining that hoarders attract attention not because they are mentally ill but because they challenge normal modes of material relations. Piled high with detailed and, at times, disturbing descriptions of uncleanliness, The Hoarders delivers a sweeping and fascinating history of hoarding that will cause us all to reconsider how we view these accumulators of clutter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHoarders. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh  acompulsive behavior, behavioral sciences, psychology, obsessions, clutter professionals, clutterologists, in-depth examination, 20th century, modern hoarders, deviance, united states, america, decaying food, mental health problems, inherent deviation, historical phenomenon, material cultures, mentally ill, normal modes, uncleanliness, public opinion, hoarding, old rubbish.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022617168540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226171852423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226171852/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles